<TEXT>
the nations largest presbyterian body monday 
called on israel to end its 20year occupation of the west bank and 
gaza strip where the church said israel had used repressive 
measures to quell palestinian violence 
the 200th general assembly of the presbyterian church declined 
to include in its resolution language calling on palestinians to 
recognize israels right to exist as a nation 
the rev benjamin weir a presbyterian leader and former hostage 
in lebanon told the 630 commissioners the palestine liberation 
organization has made such statements several times israel 
maintains that such plo statements have been ambiguous or 
unauthoritative 
the statement adopted monday on a 49467 vote said israel had 
responded to uprisings in the occupied territories with rigid 
censorship mass arrests torture of prisoners administrative 
detention and deportation 
the resolutions adopted also call upon the palestinian people 
and leadership to exert sustained efforts to control acts of 
violence in order to facilitate the peace process 
earlier monday a major presbyterian statement on nuclear war 
was revised to make the document more closely follow the original 
intention according to the two former seminary professors who led 
the writing effort 
the committee on peacemaking and international relations of the 
presbyterian church usa continued review monday evening of 
christian obedience in a nuclear age making minor changes in 
the recommendations of a subcommittee that extensively reviewed the 
paper 
the major change by the peacemaking committee was made at the 
suggestion of the rev arnold come former president of the san 
francisco theological seminary and a cochairman of the task force 
that wrote the paper last year 
originally the paper said nuclear war and the theory of nuclear 
deterrence were both immoral but the subcommittee revised that to 
say nuclear deterrence has been in danger of becoming an end in 
itself rather than an interim measure of selfdefense such a 
policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible 
come and the rev albert c winn the task forces cochairman 
and former president of the louisville ky theological seminary 
complained the phrase as an end in itself was ambiguous 
at comes suggestion the language was clarified to say nuclear 
deterrence is being regarded as an adequate and permanent means 
to national security and that is not morally defensible 
the committee has yet to deal with the major question of the 
subcommittees recommendation that the christian obedience paper be 
adopted as church policy 
the subcommittee which met for parts of four days amended the 
paper to make it clear presbyterians considered obedience to 
government the normal course 
winn said he disliked many changes but added in many 
respects they clarified the paper and deleted some statements that 
were not carefully worded 
supporters of the original paper expect many of the revisions 
including elimination of a recommendation that the church aid tax 
resisters would be restored in some form in the full committee 
opponents of the paper want it to be sent back to the churches 
for further study an effort to get the subcommittee to recommend 
that delay was defeated 95 and the subcommittee eventually agreed 
to recommend the revised report as a church policy by a 151 vote 
the report is not expected to come before the 630 delegates 
until tuesday the nineday meeting adjourns at noon wednesday 
the resolution on the middle east also 
asks israel to cease the systematic violation of human rights 
of palestinians end the policies andor practices of beatings 
and of food and fuel embargoes in the attempt to subjugate and 
break the will of the palestinian population end the 
settlements policy and the acquisition of land within the occupied 
territories since they provoke the arab peoples and reduce the 
opportunity for a peaceful resolution 
asks the united states to discourage retaliation as a 
counterterror strategy in the middle east and to address the 
injustices which are among the root causes of terrorism insist 
that weapons supplied by the us for israels defense not be used 
against civilian populations in the occupied territories or in 
aggressive attacks or disproportionate retaliation upon other 
countries and that further military and security assistance to 
israel be contingent upon the honoring of these principles 
ask all parties to participate in a united nationssponsored 
international peace conference 
the agenda included discussion of several decisions including 
the recommendation that the pension board headquarters remain in 
philadelphia a minority report suggests the board be moved to 
atlanta 
the headquarters of the 3 millionmember denomination was moved 
to louisville ky last year 
antiabortion groups also have objected to the pension boards 
paying for abortions the denomination has adopted a generally 
prochoice position condemning abortion as a method of birth 
control but saying it remains a decision by a woman her physician 
and her conscience antiabortionists say the pension board should 
not pay for abortions 
another committee has recommended the denomination undertake a 
new study on the issue of abortion 
</TEXT>
