<TEXT>
consumer groups are criticizing a compromise 
bill fashioned by the house energy and commerce committee saying 
the measure will make it harder for victims of unsafe products to 
recover damages from manufacturers 
both sides in the protracted struggle between business and 
consumer lobbyists agree however that there is virtually no 
chance the socalled product liability bill will pass congress in 
this election year 
the measure will go next to the house judiciary committee which 
shares jurisdiction over the issue but has balked at approving such 
legislation in the past even if it manages to reach the house 
which many congressional observers doubt the senate is considered 
a graveyard for product liability bills 
the measure eagerly sought by corporations worried about 
escalating liability costs would impose a uniform federal standard 
of liability preempting a wide variety of conflicting state laws 
consumer activists complain that the new proposed federal 
standard would limit victims of hazardous products to six narrow 
grounds for suing manufacturers for damages negligence 
intentional wrongdoing defect design defective construction 
inadequate warnings and breach of written warranty 
another major feature contested by consumer advocates is the 
state of the art defense available to manufacturers 
this provision says that a manufacturer can escape liability for 
damages if it can prove it did not know or could not know of a 
design defect with knowledge reasonably available to experts 
or if there were no feasible alternative design 
a proconsumer escape hatch sponsored by rep mike synar 
dokla would require only that the plaintiff prove that the 
product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should 
not have been marketed the committee also accepted synars 
proposal easing the standard of proof that plaintiffs must meet 
the synar provision also would put a burden of proof on the 
manufacturer to show that a design defect could not be discovered 
and that an alternative design was not feasible 
consumer lobbyists are unhappy though with synars proposal to 
give a judge not a trial jury the responsibility for deciding 
whether a product was so unsafe it should never have been marketed 
even with synars softening of the probusiness features of the 
original bill consumer groups say the measure undermines the legal 
doctrine of strict liability used by 47 states and favored by 
victim advocates 
that doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the 
manufacturers alleged misconduct to the defective product itself 
relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or 
should have known about its product 
consumer lobbyists argue that even though the bill makes strict 
liability a national standard in deciding damage suits it is 
weakened by including a stateoftheart defense against 
manufacturers liability which currently is allowed in only eight 
states 
not covered by the bill are tobacco alcohol and asbestos those 
products would continue to be subject to generally more stringent 
state liability laws 
the bill also includes a provision backed by antiabortionists 
that would deny special protection to any drug or contraceptive 
device that induces abortions 
</TEXT>
