<TEXT>
former gov evan mecham has lost a 
mistrial bid on the eve of closing arguments in his trial on 
charges of concealing a 350000 campaign loan 
attorneys were to give closing arguments this morning and the 
jury was expected to begin deliberations in the afternoon 
mecham and his brother willard are charged in the maricopa 
county superior court trial with concealing the 350000 loan in 
financial reports required by the state 
in a motion for mistrial defense attorney michael scott 
contended that judge michael ryan may have prejudiced the case by 
expressing surprise when the prosecution and defense said friday 
they had no more witnesses 
the defense rested its case without calling either evan or 
willard mecham to the stand after the prosecution said it had no 
rebuttal witnesses ryan told the jurors the sudden close of 
testimony had taken him by surprise 
scott argued monday that the judges statement could be 
interpreted by the jury as implying that the defense should have 
presented more testimony or put the defendants on the stand 
but ryan said he made the comment in the context of the trial 
schedule in addition he said he did not see how the defense could 
be harmed since he made the remark afterthe prosecution said it had 
no rebuttal witnesses 
ryan also denied a defense request monday that he interview each 
juror privately to find out if any had seen any publicity about the 
case 
mecham was charged with six felony counts of perjury willful 
concealment and filing false documents and faces up to 22 years in 
prison if convicted willard mecham who was his younger brothers 
1986 campaign treasurer faced three similar counts and up to 9 
years in prison if convicted 
the defense has contended the 350000 loan from developer barry 
wolfson was properly reported as part of a 465000 lump sum listed 
as a contribution from mecham and that the failure to itemize the 
loan was an innocent mistake 
former top mecham aide edith richardson said the loan was common 
knowledge among the former republican governors inner circle but 
two other former top aides donna carlson and mac matheson said 
they did not know about it 
the prosecution has said that mecham badly needed the loan to 
keep his gubernatorial campaign afloat but wanted to keep it secret 
to avoid harming the candidates theme of being beholden to no 
one 
in addition prosecutors said it didnt matter whether mechams 
closest aides knew about the loan because it was not reported to 
the public 
mecham took office in january 1987 and was removed april 4 when 
the state senate convicted him of two unrelated charges he also 
was impeached in connection with the loan but the senate decided 
not to hear that charge for fear of prejudicing his criminal trial 
