<DOCNO> AP880614-0053 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an anchorage buildingmaterials 
supplier is taking advantage of a loophole in postal regulations to 
mail 6000 concrete blocks to a remote village 700 miles away 
the shipments across alaska could end up costing the us postal 
service 500000 and even the air carrier that stands to profit 
thinks the mail system is being abused 
sam krogstad of bush consolidators which specializes in sending 
construction materials via the mail says the postal services 
losses are partly selfinflicted because the postal system pays 10 
times as much to send the building materials by air freight as it 
charges krogstad to mail them 
each individually addressed concrete block costs krogstad 433 
in postage the same block costs the post office 5094 to deliver 
to wainwright an arctic ocean eskimo community about 90 miles 
southwest of barrow thats a subsidy of 4661 per block 
krogstad also is mailing 4600 bags of cement to wainwright 
the blocks each weigh 67 pounds and the bags of cement about 65 
pounds so they fall just under the parcelpost limit of 70 pounds 
to qualify as mail his postage costs will total about 45000 
the blocks and bags could have been shipped via air freight from 
anchorage for a little more than 210000 but the way mail is 
handled in rural alaska more than doubles the cost 
first the postal service trucks the blocks to fairbanks about 
360 miles they are then flown to barrow on large cargo planes 
transferred to small planes and flown to wainwright in loads of 18 
to 35 blocks 
the practice is called bypass mail because the shipment 
moves directly from sender to airline to addressee bypassing post 
offices 
this was not the intent of the bypass program says tim 
dorgan a postal service transportation supervisor the original 
intent of bypass mail was to clear the postal floor of large 
shipments of groceries and staples required for daytoday living 
but krogstad says the system means his shipments cost the postal 
service 76 cents a pound from fairbanks to wainwright instead of 
the 30 cents a pound that a charter flight from anchorage to 
wainwright would cost 
its ridiculous krogstad said its unamerican its got 
to be unconstitutional that a branch of the us government cant 
go out and competitively bid to get the best price on hauling the 
mail 
even one of the prime beneficiaries of the blocklift has 
misgivings 
were philosophically opposed to it says don brugman 
president of northern air cargo which is hauling many of the 
blocks and cement bags its not what the mail is for 
dorgan says hes worried the blocklift may put an end to bypass 
mail once word gets around the people in the bush are the ones 
who are going to suffer he said 
another problem says dorgan is that the blocklift may cause a 
backup of ordinary mail such as groceries bound for villages 
served from barrow 
the idea of mailing the materials was an angle that got us the 
job said bob gilman owner of gilco construction a contractor 
building a smallboat harbor at wainwright with the blocks 
he says he feels bad but it is just an angle and thats the 
nature of the business were in 
