<TEXT>
a us supreme court ruling on vaccine liability 
focused on the only common vaccine that can cause the disease it is 
intended to prevent experts say 
the court ruled monday that the federal government may be forced 
to pay damages for polio resulting from the oral vaccine for that 
disease 
but in general side effects from vaccines are rare and its 
far better to be vaccinated than to get the disease said g 
scott giebink professor of pediatrics at the university of 
minnesota medical school 
here are common vaccines and their side effects 
oral polio vaccine which is given twice in the first year of 
life with boosters in the second year and just before entering 
school it has no side effects other than rare cases of polio 
paralysis which occurs in about one out of every 32 million doses 
of vaccine giebink said 
the paralytic reaction is most common in people with hampered 
immune systems either the vaccinated child or a family member of a 
vaccinated child he said the weakened virus used in the vaccine 
can pass to a family member possibly causing trouble if that 
persons immune system is weakened he said 
diphtheriatetanuspertussis vaccine given at ages two 
months four months six months 15 months and at entry to school 
pertussis is whooping cough 
about one in 110000 children who get the dtp vaccine develop a 
brain dysfunction that can include seizures it is usually 
temporary but about one in 310000 vaccinated children get 
permanent damage that includes mental retardation or movement 
difficulties according to the centers for disease control 
whether those problems are caused by the vaccine is 
controversial said samuel katz chairman of the pediatrics 
department at the duke university medical center 
giebink said they appear to be linked to the vaccine because its 
more mild side effects may lead to a doctors examination which 
uncovers the serious problem that may gone unnoticed before the 
inoculation 
the mild side effects include muscle soreness and swelling at 
the injection site which occur in about half the injections and 
fever in about onefifth of immunizations he said about one in 
2000 children develops a fever and convulsions without lasting 
effects he said 
haemophilus influenzae type b vaccine given at age 18 months 
the disease being prevented is a potentially fatal infection that 
can cause brain damage pneumonia and other effects 
the vaccine has no serious side effects giebink said fewer 
than 1 percent of recipients get a fever and one in five have arm 
soreness or tenderness 
measlesmumpsrubella vaccine given at age 15 months no 
serious side effects are known although in very rare cases a spell 
of fever and convulsions can follow the shot giebink said 
some children get a rash or slight fever lasting a few days 
about one in seven have a mild swelling of lymph glands in the 
neck about one in 50 teenage or adult women experience a 
shortlived aching or swelling of joints he said 
influenza vaccine given mostly to people in highrisk groups 
such as those with chronic lung or heart disease and the elderly 
despite publicity about a paralysis called guillainbarre syndrome 
associated with swine flu vaccines in 1976 flu vaccines in general 
cause no serious side effects giebink and katz said 
