retaliation upon other countries 
asked all parties to participate in a united nationssponsored 
international peace conference 
today the assembly was to begin discussing its statement on 
christian obedience in a nuclear age 
the statement which stemmed from a request five years ago by 
local presbyterian groups for guidance on how to respond to tax 
resisters was revised in lengthy meetings at the assembly by three 
committees 
the recommendations were edited to make it clear that while tax 
resistance and other acts of civil disobedience could be justified 
christians normally are expected to obey civil authorities 
the statement was edited in an effort to remove any doubt that 
disobedience is not a normal course a section was added saying 
military service could be an appropriate response to a christians 
conscience 
the committees reworded discussion of nuclear deterrence but 
left alone the declaration that nuclear war itself is immoral 
the original paper said nuclear deterrence assumes the 
willingness to use such weapons and is therefore immoral although 
it said unilateral disarmament is not yet feasible 
the final recommended statement said nuclear deterrence has 
been in danger of being regarded as an adequate and permanent means 
to national security rather an interim measure of selfdefense 
such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible 
the presbyterians also were to elect the stated clerk who is 
the officer responsible for overseeing the assemblys operation 
