the foreign press association of israel on 
tuesday protested about 150 incidents of brutality against 
journalists by police and soldiers 
the 200member association issued the statement at a news 
conference and focused on an incident in which police beat up two 
foreign photograpers at a demonstration in tel aviv this month the 
beating was witnessed by other photographers 
we demand that the ministry of police investigate and punish 
those who took part in that incident said robert slater the 
chairman of the press association we deplore the statements by 
public officials that have created an odious public atmosphere 
all the incidents protested occurred in the past six months 
slater a correspondent for time magazine said government 
officials had made repeated statements indicating that the foreign 
press fanned the flames of the arab uprising which began dec 8 
he said such statements left in the minds of the public the 
idea that we have orchestrated events paid kids to throw stones 
and this has encouraged 19 and 20yearold soldiers to do 
their thing as they see fit 
in the june 4 tel aviv incident photographers sven nackstrand 
of agence france press and andre brutmann of alfa press were beaten 
by plainclothes and uniformed police while they photographed a 
demonstration against israels occupation of the west bank and gaza 
strip 
i was hit in all directions and struck to the ground i 
received five or six hard hits on the head and one felt like an 
explosion nackstrand told reporters 
nackstrand who has worked seven years in israel said he was 
then thrown near a police van and a few minutes later pulled into 
the van he was held in the van for about 10 minutes until a senior 
officer apparently realizing he was a journalist ordered him 
released 
slater said the police ministry didnt answer a cable sent a 
week ago protesting the incident 
police ministry spokeswoman mira firestein said her office 
received the cable and asked police in tel aviv to investigate and 
was still awaiting a reply 
