the government is moving quickly to lower taxes 
for cooperative ventures before a new law enters force july 1 the 
official soviet news agency tass said tuesday 
the new measure broadens the rights of the thousands of 
independent enterprises that are key to kremlin leader mikhail 
gorbachevs reform movement 
the announcement was a victory for those supporting gorbachevs 
efforts to reform the soviet economy and to provide a better 
quality and selection of consumer goods and services 
last month the supreme soviet the nominal national parliament 
passed a law ensuring that cooperatives owned by their members 
rather than the state can compete on an equal footing with 
staterun businesses 
it allows cooperatives to earn hard currency prohibits 
government interference in their business and bars the state from 
taking them over 
but it would have left in place a new tax ladder set up by the 
finance ministry forcing cooperatives to pay the state up to 90 
percent of profits 
supreme soviet deputies called for a change complaining that 
the taxes would strangle the cooperatives 
a leading reform advocate economist nikolai shmelev had told a 
news conference rewriting the tax law might take as long as a year 
but tass said government experts will have the new tax law ready 
in weeks 
significant changes are expected to be made to the decree 
tass said they say in particular that progressive taxes on 
coops will be reduced to 60 percent and even possibly 50 percent 
from the current 90 
members of the coops most needed by society for example 
building ones as well as cooperatives selling their products at 
state prices will most likely be exempted from progressive 
taxation altogether 
