<TEXT>
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan 
said tuesday that a further decline in the dollar may hurt rather 
than help efforts to reduce the us trade deficit 
greenspan in a speech to the economic club of new york said 
the devaluation of the dollar over the past three years has helped 
narrow the trade gap by dampening demand for more expensive foreign 
goods in the united states and stimulating sales of cheaper us 
goods overseas 
however greenspan said it is questionable whether the united 
states has the capacity to boost production of exports any faster 
than the current growth rate 
thus further declines in the dollar by raising the price of 
imports could actually cause the deficit to grow he said 
i find no adjustment benefit to be derived from a further fall 
in the dollar he said in a text of his speech released in 
washington 
in three years the dollar has lost about half of its value when 
measured against the japanese yen it rose somewhat in trading 
tuesday on the news that the us trade deficit for april had 
fallen to 99 billion its lowest level in nearly 3 years 
it was the second time in less than a week that greenspan has 
spoken against a further drop in the dollar he issued a similar 
warning june 8 after meeting in chicago with other nations central 
bankers 
rather than devaluing the dollar greenspan said in new york 
reducing our federal budget deficit would be the most important 
step we can take in the adjustment process 
on another topic greenspan said despite strained capacity in 
steel and certain chemicals statistics on industrial delivery 
times do not indicate that inflationary bottlenecks are developing 
delivery times for production materials have moved up only 
moderately since late 1985 and have stabilized at least 
temporarily during the past five months he said 
