<TEXT>
a continuing decline in the number of us 
business starts reflects the nations changing economic profile and 
not necessarily broad economic problems according to a business 
information concern 
the number of new domestic businesses declined by 66 percent to 
53382 in the first three months of the year the seventh straight 
quarterly drop from 57158 in first quarter 1987 according to 
dun amp bradstreet corp 
dun amp bradstreet officials cited the maturing of the nations 
economic expansion now in its sixth year and a shift from 
consumerism to exportdriven growth as factors in the decline of 
business starts a barometer of economic activity and moneymaking 
opportunities 
joseph w duncan dun amp bradstreets corporate economist and 
chief statistician said new retailing businesses fell because of 
expectations that consumer demand will weaken and startups of new 
service businesses fell in response to increased competition and 
corporate budget reductions 
retailing and service concerns account for about half of all new 
businesses 
while the current surge in us exports will create new 
business opportunities in some sectors existing manufacturers are 
the primary beneficiaries duncan said in a report of the latest 
figures 
business starts are considered important because they signal the 
level of entrepreneurial activity and perceived opportunities for 
profit in local area markets but a persistent decline in starts 
does not necessarily indicate a broader economic problem said reid 
gearhart a dun amp bradstreet spokesman 
with the recovery in its sixth year thats just having a 
dampening effect he said its not really a negative 
dun amp bradstreet data indicated firstquarter business starts 
fell in seven of the nine major industry sectors the largest 
decrease came in the financeinsurancereal estate category which 
fell 98 percent retail business starts dropped 81 percent and 
services fell 57 percent 
starts also fell in the construction manufacturing wholesale 
and transportation sectors with decreases of between 5 percent and 
8 percent 
increases were in agriculture up 115 percent and mining up 
23 percent 
both mining which includes oil and gas extraction businesses 
and agriculture appear to be turning the corner after several years 
of severe stress duncan said 
despite a drop in manufacturingrelated business starts there 
was evidence that export growth was encouraging some entrepreneurs 
duncan said an analysis of manufacturing starts showed significant 
increases among motor vehicle and equipment makers metal producers 
and office equipment manufacturers 
geographically firstquarter starts fell nationwide with the 
largest decreases in the rocky mountain states down 156 percent 
other significant drops occurred in the middle atlantic states 
down 122 percent and the west north central states down 12 
percent 
starts in new england dropped only 11 percent while starts in 
the south atlantic and east north central states were both down 33 
percent starts fell 38 percent in the pacific states 67 percent 
in east south central states and 63 percent in west south central 
states 
dun amp bradstreet describes itself as the worlds largest 
marketer of business information and related services with revenue 
of 34 billion in 1987 
</TEXT>
