<TEXT>
financial markets rallied powerfully tuesday in response to a 
stunning drop in the us monthly trade deficit oil prices rose 
after opec extended a production pact and american automakers 
reported lower sales for early june 
the biggest economic news was the commerce departments report 
that the april trade deficit shrank to 989 billion the best 
showing in more than three years 
many economists had expected a wider deficit assuming exports 
would not not sustain high levels and imports would surge but 
exports declined only slightly and imports plunged dampening fears 
that the economy is growing too rapidly and acute inflation is 
inevitable 
the news was greeted enthusiastically in the dollar bond and 
stock markets the dollar leaped in value against most major 
foreign currencies rising 17 percent against the british pound 
16 percent against the west german mark and 11 percent against 
the japanese yen 
in the bond market a sensitive barometer of interest rates the 
key 30year treasury issue jumped more than 20 per 1000 in face 
amount and its yield fell to 881 percent the lowest point in two 
months 
the bond rally spilled into stocks where prices surged and the 
key dow jones industrial average rose 2507 points to 212447 its 
highest close since the october crash broader market barometers 
also hit postcrash highs 
elsewhere oil prices rose after the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries decided to prolong an outputrestraint pact 
until the end of the year 
on the new york mercantile exchange the july contract for west 
texas intermediate the us benchmark crude oil rose 40 cents to 
settle at 1683 per 42gallon barrel 
in other economic news major automakers said sales of 
domestically built cars and light trucks fell 41 percent in early 
june from last years levels for the same period 
but industry analysts attributed the decline largely to buying 
incentives last year that inflated sales they said that 1988 
spring sales have held steady and consumer confidence remains 
strong 
car sales were down for all domestic makers except toyota motor 
corp which was just beginning us production last year and 
mazda motor corp which began us production in september 
